Use the mental health study data to graphically explore the relationship of life events and SES on mental health impairment. Your graph should illustrate whether SES moderates the influence of life events on mental health.

# read in mh data
mh_data <- read_csv(here("Data", "Mental Health Study Data.csv"))

── Column specification ──────────────────────────────────────────────
cols(
  MentImp = col_double(),
  LifeEvts = col_double(),
  SES = col_double()
)
# break SES into three groups
mh_data$SES_groups <- cut(mh_data$SES, breaks = 3) %>% 
  factor(., labels = c("lower third", "middle third", "upper third"))
  
# plot the moderating relationship of ses
ggplot(mh_data) +
  aes(x = LifeEvts, y = MentImp, color = mh_data$SES_groups) +
  geom_point(color = "grey") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(x="Life Events", y="Mental Impairment", color="SES") 

NA
NA

There is a positive relationship bt life events and mental impairment, and this is stronger for individuals from lower SES.

12

Use the notes study data to graphically explore the relationship of method of note taking to later recall. Your graph should illustrate whether the type of lecture moderates the effect of note taking method on recall.

# read in notes data
notes_data <- read_csv(here("Data", "Notes Data.csv"))

── Column specification ──────────────────────────────────────────────
cols(
  lecture = col_double(),
  notes = col_double(),
  score = col_double()
)
notes_data$lecture_type <- factor(notes_data$lecture,
                                  levels = c(1, 2),
                                  labels = c("disorganized", "organized"))

# plot the moderating relationship of ses
ggplot(notes_data) +
  aes(x = notes, y = score, color = lecture_type) +
  geom_point(color = "grey") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(x="Type of Notes", y="Recall Test Score", color="Type of Lecture")

Type of lecture moderates the relationship between type of notes and recall test scores, such that there is a positive relationship between type of note and recall test scores in organized lectures, and a negative relationship for disorganized lectures.
